# Read the TSV file
df <- read.delim("~/kraken_out_230530/pavian_out230530/Phylum.tsv", sep = "\t", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Convert columns to numeric
df[, -1] <- sapply(df[, -1], as.numeric)

# Calculate relative values
df_relative <- df
df_relative[, -1] <- t(apply(df[, -1], 1, function(x) x/sum(x)))

# Print the resulting dataframe
#print(df_relative)

# Reshape the data to long format
df_long <- df_relative %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -Sample, names_to = "Phylum", values_to = "Percentage")

# Plot the stacked barplot
Phylum_barplot <- ggplot(df_long, aes(x = Sample, y = Percentage, fill = Phylum)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack") +
  labs(x = "Sample", y = "Relative Abundance") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "right") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Phylum")) +
  theme_minimal()+
   theme(legend.position = "right",
        legend.text = element_text(size = 12),  # Set legend text size
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14),  # Set axis title size
        legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black"))   # Set axis tick labels size

Top10-Class distribution

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tidyverse))

# Read the TSV file
df <- read.delim("~/kraken_out_230530/pavian_out230530/Class.tsv", sep = "\t", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Convert columns to numeric
df[, -1] <- sapply(df[, -1], as.numeric)

# Calculate relative values
df_relative <- df
df_relative[, -1] <- t(apply(df[, -1], 1, function(x) x/sum(x)))

# Print the resulting dataframe
#print(df_relative)

# Reshape the data to long format
df_long <- df_relative %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -Sample, names_to = "Class", values_to = "Percentage")

# Filter the top 10 most abundant families
top_10_Class <- df_long %>%
  group_by(Class) %>%
  summarise(Total_Percentage = sum(Percentage)) %>%
  top_n(10, wt = Total_Percentage) %>%
  select(Class)

df_long_filtered <- df_long %>%
  filter(Class %in% top_10_Class$Class)

# Plot the stacked barplot
Class_barplot <- ggplot(df_long_filtered, aes(x = Sample, y = Percentage, fill = Class)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack") +
  labs(x = "Sample", y = "Relative Abundance") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "right",
        legend.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black"))

Heatmap

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(stringr))

# Read the TSV file
df <- read.delim("~/kraken_out_230530/pavian_out230530/Species.tsv", sep = "\t", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Convert columns to numeric
df[, -1] <- sapply(df[, -1], as.numeric)

# Create a matrix with the data
data_matrix <- as.matrix(df[, -1])

# Set row names
rownames(data_matrix) <- df[, 1]

# Calculate the sum of values for each species
species_sums <- rowSums(data_matrix)

# Calculate relative abundance along samples
df_long <- reshape2::melt(data_matrix)
df_long$relative_abundance <- df_long$value / species_sums[df_long$Var1]
df_long$relative_abundance[is.na(df_long$relative_abundance)] <- 0

# Replace full stops with spaces in the Var2 column
df_long$Var2 <- str_replace(df_long$Var2, "\\.", " ")

# Generate the heatmap using ggplot with updated relative abundance and separated species names
Species_heatmap <- ggplot(df_long, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = relative_abundance)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "grey1", mid = "white", high = "orange", midpoint = 0.5, limits = c(0, 1), na.value = "gray", breaks = c(0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1)) +
  labs(x = "Sample", y = "Species", fill = "Relative Abundance") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(margin = margin(l = 10), size = 8, face = "italic", colour = "black"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black"),
    plot.margin = margin(t = 50, r = 10, b = 30, l = 50, unit = "pt")
  )

Community composition analysis: You can explore the relative abundance of different species or taxonomic groups across samples using ordination techniques like Principal Component Analysis (PCA) or Non-Metric Multidimensional Scaling (NMDS). This can help identify patterns and similarities/dissimilarities in community composition.

Alpha diversity

# Load the required packages
library(vegan)
library(ggplot2)

# Read the OTU table or abundance matrix
data_main <- read.csv("~/kraken_out_230530/pavian_out230530/New_classification/Species.tsv", sep = "\t", header = TRUE, row.names = 1)
data <- data.frame(t(data_main))

# Calculate alpha diversity indices (e.g., Shannon, Simpson, Inverse Simpson)
diversity_indices <- c("shannon", "simpson", "invsimpson")
alpha_diversity <- list()
for (index in diversity_indices) {
  alpha_diversity[[index]] <- diversity(data, index = index)
}

# Create a data frame with alpha diversity values
alpha_diversity_df <- data.frame(
  Site = rep(rownames(data), times = length(diversity_indices)),
  Index = rep(diversity_indices, each = nrow(data)),
  Diversity = unlist(alpha_diversity)
)

# Create a ggplot with alpha diversity indices and color-coded groups
ggplot(alpha_diversity_df, aes(x = Site, y = Diversity, color = Index, shape = Index)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  labs(x = "Sample", y = "Diversity") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("shannon" = "grey40", "simpson" = "grey", "invsimpson" = "grey10")) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c("shannon" = 16, "simpson" = 17, "invsimpson" = 18)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "right",
        legend.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12, colour = "black"))
